INPUT: {
  "pageId": "f6d58b33-e8dd-401b-b141-95f02ac46060",
  "blockType": "blocks",
  "data": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 1,
        "textColor": "blue",
        "backgroundColor": "blue"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "React Basics",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true,
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "green"
      },
      "content": "What is React?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "backgroundColor": "green"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "React is a free and open-source front-end JavaScript library for building user interfaces based on UI components. It's maintained by Meta and a community of individual developers and companies. React can be used to develop single-page, mobile, or server-rendered applications with frameworks like Next.js.",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "purple"
      },
      "content": "Core Concepts"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3,
        "textColor": "orange"
      },
      "content": "1. Components"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "backgroundColor": "orange"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "React applications are built using components, which are independent, reusable pieces of UI. Think of them as custom, isolated HTML elements that return React elements to be rendered to the page. They can be function components or class components.",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3,
        "textColor": "red"
      },
      "content": "2. JSX (JavaScript XML)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "backgroundColor": "red"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "JSX is a syntax extension for JavaScript that looks a lot like HTML. It allows you to write HTML-like code directly within your JavaScript files. React then uses this JSX to describe what the UI should look like. It's not required to use JSX, but it makes React code much cleaner and easier to read.",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3,
        "textColor": "blue"
      },
      "content": "3. State"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "backgroundColor": "blue"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "State refers to data that changes over time within a component. It's private to a component and fully controlled by it. When a component's state changes, React re-renders the component to reflect the new data. This is how interactive elements update on the screen.",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3,
        "textColor": "green"
      },
      "content": "4. Props (Properties)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "backgroundColor": "green"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Props are how data is passed from a parent component to a child component. They are read-only, meaning a child component cannot directly modify the props it receives from its parent. This creates a unidirectional data flow, making applications easier to understand and debug.",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "brown"
      },
      "content": "Getting Started with React"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "props": {
        "backgroundColor": "brown"
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The easiest way to get started with React is to use ",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Vite",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true,
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " or ",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Create React App",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true,
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ". These tools set up a modern web development environment, allowing you to focus on writing your React code. You'll typically need Node.js installed to use these tools. After setting up, you can create your first component and start building!",
          "styles": {
            "textColor": "white"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
