INPUT: {
  "pageId": "8aa3f1fc-1a12-40dd-a2b2-6b7fce5c5947",
  "blockType": "blocks",
  "data": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": "Chapter 2: Acids, Bases and Salts"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "This document, \"Chapter 2: Acids, Bases and Salts,\" introduces fundamental concepts related to these chemical substances."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "1. Introduction to Acids and Bases"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Acids are typically sour and turn blue litmus red; bases are bitter and turn red litmus blue."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Acids and bases neutralize each other's effects."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Indicators (like litmus, turmeric, phenolphthalein, methyl orange) change color to show if a substance is acidic or basic. Olfactory indicators (like onion, vanilla, clove oil) change odor."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "2. Chemical Properties of Acids and Bases"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Acids react with Metals:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Produce a salt and hydrogen gas (e.g., zinc with sulfuric acid)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Bases react with Metals:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Some bases react with metals to produce a salt and hydrogen gas (e.g., zinc with sodium hydroxide)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Acids react with Metal Carbonates/Hydrogencarbonates:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Produce a salt, carbon dioxide gas, and water (e.g., sodium carbonate with HCl). Carbon dioxide turns limewater milky."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Acids and Bases react (Neutralization):",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " An acid reacts with a base to form a salt and water, cancelling out their properties (e.g., HCl + NaOH → NaCl + H2O)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Metallic Oxides are Basic:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " They react with acids to form salt and water."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Non-metallic Oxides are Acidic:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " They react with bases to form salt and water."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "3. What Acids and Bases Have in Common"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Aqueous Solutions Conduct Electricity:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Acids and bases form ions in water (H+ from acids, OH- from bases), allowing them to conduct electricity. Compounds like glucose and alcohol, though containing hydrogen, do not form ions and thus don't show acidic behavior or conduct electricity."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Ion Formation in Water:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Acids produce H+ ions (which exist as hydronium ions, H3O+) in aqueous solutions, responsible for their acidic properties. Bases produce OH- ions in water. Water-soluble bases are called alkalis."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Dilution:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " The process of mixing an acid or base with water is highly exothermic. It's crucial to add acid slowly to water, not the other way around, to prevent splashing and excessive heat. Dilution decreases the concentration of H3O+ or OH- ions."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "4. Strength of Acid or Base Solutions (pH Scale)"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "pH Scale:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " A scale from 0 to 14 used to measure hydrogen ion concentration. pH < 7 indicates an acidic solution, pH = 7 is neutral, and pH > 7 indicates a basic (alkaline) solution. Lower pH means higher H+ concentration and stronger acidity."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Strength vs. Concentration:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Strong acids/bases produce many H+/OH- ions, while weak acids/bases produce fewer, even at the same concentration."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "Importance of pH in Everyday Life"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Biological Systems:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Living organisms thrive within a narrow pH range (e.g., human body pH 7.0-7.8)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Acid Rain:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Rainwater with pH below 5.6 harms aquatic life."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Soil pH:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Important for healthy plant growth."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Digestion:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Stomach produces HCl for digestion; indigestion is treated with antacids (bases)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Tooth Decay:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Occurs when mouth pH drops below 5.5, corroding tooth enamel. Basic toothpastes help neutralize acids."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Self-Defense:",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Animals and plants use acids for defense (e.g., bee stings, nettle stings secrete methanoic acid, which can be neutralized by mild bases)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "5. More About Salts"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "Salt Families"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Salts can be grouped by common positive or negative radicals."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "pH of Salts"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Salts of strong acid + strong base are neutral (pH 7)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Salts of strong acid + weak base are acidic (pH < 7)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Salts of strong base + weak acid are basic (pH > 7)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "Chemicals from Common Salt (NaCl)"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "NaCl is a raw material for various industrial chemicals:"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "props": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Sodium Hydroxide (NaOH):",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Produced by the chlor-alkali process (electrolysis of brine), yielding NaOH, chlorine (Cl2), and hydrogen (H2)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "props": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Bleaching Powder (Ca(ClO)2):",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Formed by reacting chlorine with dry slaked lime. Used for bleaching, as an oxidizing agent, and to disinfect water."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "props": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Baking Soda (Sodium Hydrogencarbonate, NaHCO3):",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " A mild basic salt used in baking powder (releases CO2 for rising), as an antacid, and in soda-acid fire extinguishers."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "props": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Washing Soda (Sodium Carbonate Decahydrate, Na2CO3.10H2O):",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " Used in glass, soap, and paper industries, for making borax, as a cleaning agent, and for removing water hardness."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "Water of Crystallisation"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Many salts, though appearing dry, contain a fixed number of water molecules chemically bound within their crystal structure (e.g., copper sulphate, CuSO4.5H2O, is blue; becomes white when water is removed by heating)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "Plaster of Paris (Calcium Sulphate Hemihydrate, CaSO4.½H2O)"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Formed by heating gypsum (CaSO4.2H2O). It is a white powder that, when mixed with water, sets into a hard solid (gypsum), used for supporting fractured bones, making toys, and decorative materials."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
