--- updatePage called at 2026-03-27T19:40:15.928Z ---
INPUT: {
  "pageId": "911bb63a-e922-4010-9f92-02dadf60ad48",
  "blockType": "blocks",
  "data": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 1,
        "textColor": "blue"
      },
      "content": "Agent Memory Series: Building Your Personalized AI Agent"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "This series will guide you through managing your agent's memory to build truly personalized AI agents. Over three episodes, you'll learn how to give your AI agent real memory, step-by-step."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "purple"
      },
      "content": "Series Overview"
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Episode 1: Short-Term Memory",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " - Learn how your agent remembers what you said earlier in the same conversation. We'll fix memory loss in a trip planning agent using ADK sessions and session services."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Episode 2: Persistent User Preferences",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " - Move from in-memory storage to a database to build a simple user preference store, allowing agents to remember facts (e.g., 'you're vegetarian') across new conversations."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Episode 3: Long-Term Memory",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " - Utilize Vortex AI memory bank service to enable agents to recall facts from past conversations, including images, video, and audio, using a preload memory tool."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "By the end, you'll be able to build AI agents that remember conversations and past experiences across time and media."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "green"
      },
      "content": "Episode 1: Agent Short-Term Memory & Sessions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "First, let's understand what a ",
          "styles": {}
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "session",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " means. A session is one continuous conversation, like a single chat thread on your phone."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "In ADK web UI, it defaults to an in-memory session service."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "If you create a new session, the agent behaves as if it's meeting you for the first time, unable to access previous conversation history."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3,
        "textColor": "red"
      },
      "content": "Problem: The Memory Loss Example"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Consider a trip planning agent:"
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "content": "Turn 1: User asks, \"Plan a two-day trip to Lisbon.\" The agent plans Day 1."
    },
    {
      "type": "numberedListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Turn 2: User says, \"Perfect. Plan Day 2.\"",
          "styles": {}
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " – If a new session is created, the agent forgets everything (city, plan, user interests) and starts over.",
          "styles": {
            "italic": true
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3,
        "textColor": "green"
      },
      "content": "The Solution: Using the Same Session"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "By creating and reusing a single session across multiple turns, the agent can retain context."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "With the same session, if you ask \"Plan Day 2\" at Turn 3, the agent can look back at the full conversation and adapt the plan. This is the ",
          "styles": {}
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "magic of sessions",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ".",
          "styles": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "blue"
      },
      "content": "Key Components Inside a Session"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "1. Events"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "This is like the transcript of every user message and agent reply, including user media input (e.g., image data)."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Provides the agent with conversation context, allowing it to read earlier messages."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 3
      },
      "content": "2. State"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Think of this as a small 'sticky note' for quick access to important information."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Examples: a restaurant name, a confirmation number, a travel destination."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Why use State? You don't want your model to re-read 15 messages just to find one value. State allows you to store and reuse it efficiently."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "orange"
      },
      "content": "Agent Collaboration with Session State"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Session state facilitates seamless collaboration between multiple agents:"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Example: Agent A finds a restaurant and outputs its name (e.g., mapped to a 'destination' key)."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Agent B automatically receives this 'destination' as a variable and can then provide directions."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "This enables agents to work together without constantly parsing the entire conversation transcript."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "backgroundColor": "red",
        "textColor": "default"
      },
      "content": "Important: How to Modify Session State Safely"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "NEVER ",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true,
            "textColor": "red"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "modify the session object directly in your tool code. Changes won't be recorded in the event log or saved by the persistent service.",
          "styles": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "INSTEAD",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true,
            "textColor": "green"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ", use the ",
          "styles": {}
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "context",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " that ADK provides (via tool or callback).",
          "styles": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "When you write to `context.state`, ADK records the change with the event, ensuring it can be stored and recovered when moving to database and long-term memory."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "backgroundColor": "blue",
        "textColor": "default"
      },
      "content": "Episode 1 Recap: Short-Term Memory"
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "A session represents one continuous conversation thread."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Events are like the conversation transcript, providing context."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "State is a structured 'scratchpad' for quick access to key information."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Using the same session across turns with an in-memory session service prevents memory loss."
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": "Always write state through `context` so ADK can save it for persistence."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "This provides your agent with ",
          "styles": {}
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "short-term working memory",
          "styles": {
            "bold": true
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": ", which is fast but temporary (like RAM).",
          "styles": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2,
        "textColor": "purple"
      },
      "content": "What's Next?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "In the next episode, we will add persistence to ensure your agent can survive an app restart and still remember the user, moving beyond temporary memory."
    }
  ]
}
