--- updatePage called at 2026-03-28T10:01:33.861Z ---
INPUT: {
  "pageId": "970d71a6-4d6e-482a-8457-68c2c80e6562",
  "blockType": "blocks",
  "data": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": "React Notes"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "A brief overview of key React concepts."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "1. Components"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Independent, reusable pieces of UI. They can be functional (preferred) or class-based. Components manage their own state and props, making UIs modular and maintainable."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "2. JSX (JavaScript XML)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "A syntax extension for JavaScript, allowing you to write HTML-like structures directly within your JavaScript code. It's not HTML; it gets compiled into React.createElement calls. It makes UI declaration intuitive."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "3. State"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "An object that holds some information that might change over the lifetime of the component. When state changes, the component re-renders. Managed using the 'useState' hook in functional components."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "4. Props (Properties)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Read-only attributes passed from a parent component to a child component. They allow data to flow down the component tree and are used to customize child components."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "5. Hooks"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Functions that let you 'hook into' React state and lifecycle features from functional components. "
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "useState: Manages component-specific state."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "bulletListItem",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "useEffect: Handles side effects (data fetching, subscriptions, manual DOM manipulation) after every render."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "6. Virtual DOM"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "A lightweight copy of the actual DOM, stored in memory. React uses it to improve performance by comparing the current Virtual DOM with the previous one to find differences."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "7. Reconciliation"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "The process by which React updates the actual DOM. When state or props change, React compares the new Virtual DOM with the old one (diffing) and applies only the necessary changes to the real DOM, minimizing costly updates."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "8. Conditional Rendering"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Rendering different elements or components based on certain conditions (e.g., if a user is logged in). Achieved using JavaScript operators like if statements, logical &&, or the ternary operator."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "9. List Rendering"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Displaying collections of data. Typically done using the JavaScript 'map()' array method. Each item in a list must have a unique 'key' prop to help React efficiently update the list."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "props": {
        "level": 2
      },
      "content": "10. Event Handling"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "React elements handle events similarly to DOM elements, but with some differences (e.g., camelCase for event names, passing functions directly). React's synthetic event system normalizes events across browsers."
    }
  ]
}
